{{Infobox government agency | agency_name = Bureau of Energy Resources | type = bureau | seal = U.S. Department of State official seal.svg | seal_width = 120px | seal_caption = Seal of the United States Department of State | formed = {{Start date and years ago|2011|11|16}} | preceding1 = | preceding2 = | jurisdiction = [[Executive branch of the United States]] | employees = 91 (as of 2016)<ref name="OIG">{{cite web|title=Inspection of the Bureau of Energy Resources|url=https://oig.state.gov/system/files/isp-i-16-06.pdf|publisher=[[Inspector General of the Department of State]]|date=February 2016|accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref> | budget = $16.35&nbsp;million (FY 2015)<ref name="OIG"/> | chief1_name = [[Francis R. Fannon]] | chief1_position = [[Assistant Secretary of State for Energy Resources]] | chief2_name = | chief2_position = | parent_department = [[United States Department of State|U.S. Department of State]] | website = {{url|www.state.gov/e/enr}} }}
The '''Bureau of Energy Resources''' ('''ENR''') is an agency in the [[United States Department of State]] that coordinates the department's efforts in promoting international [[energy security]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Johnson|first=Keith|title=U.S. Brings Diplomacy to Politics Of Energy|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203503204577040503083257554|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=November 16, 2011|accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Suzanne|title=Energy resource bureau aims to bring State Department out of the dark ages |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2011/nov/21/state-department-energy-resource-department|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=November 21, 2011|accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref> The bureau is under the purview of the [[Under Secretary of State for Economic Growth, Energy, and the Environment]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Department Organization Chart |url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/ei/rls/dos/99494.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=March 2014|accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref>
The head of the Bureau of Energy Resources is Assistant Secretary [[Francis R. Fannon]].
==History== The Bureau of Energy Resources was established in October 2011, following a recommendation in the 2010 [[Quadrennial Diplomacy and Development Review]] calling on the department to create a bureau uniting diplomatic and programmatic efforts in the global production and use of energy.<ref name="OIG"/><ref>{{cite web|title=State Department Launches "Bureau of Energy Resources" |url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2011/11/177262.htm|publisher=[[Spokesperson for the United States Department of State]]|date=November 16, 2011|accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The State Department's New Bureau of Energy Resources: Shaping America's Global Energy Policy|url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/pl/177233.htm|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]] |date=November 16, 2011|accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref> The new bureau combined personnel and assets previously assigned to existing energy-related offices in the department, primarily from what is now the [[Bureau of Economic and Business Affairs]].<ref name="OIG"/>
==Organization== [[File:ENR chart.png|thumb|right|250px|Organizational chart of the Bureau of Energy Resources]] The bureau is headed by the Special Envoy and Coordinator for International Energy Affairs, who is appointed by the [[United States Secretary of State]].<ref name="OIG"/> Four Deputy Assistant Secretaries also oversee different divisions of the bureau, namely Energy Diplomacy, Energy Transformation, Energy Governance and Access, and Bureau Implementation and Coordination.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bureau of Energy Resources (ENR)|url=https://fam.state.gov/FAM/01FAM/01FAM0460.html|work=[[Foreign Affairs Manual]]|date=October 22, 2012|accessdate=April 4, 2016}}</ref> Six unique offices exist within the bureau: *Office of Europe, the Western Hemisphere, and Africa *Office of the Middle East and Asia *Office of Alternative and Renewable Energy *Office of Electricity and Energy Efficiency *Office of Policy Analysis and Public Diplomacy *Office of Energy Programs
The bureau manages three foreign assistance programs with a total FY 2014 budget of $11.8&nbsp;million in economic support funds. ENR relies heavily on interagency agreements with the Departments of [[United States Department of the Interior|Interior]], [[United States Department of Commerce|Commerce]], and [[United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury]], as well as on contracted private-sector firms, to implement technical assistance.<ref name="OIG"/>
